{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":79760,"duration_api_ms":79718,"num_turns":10,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"d79e6c36-6885-4f26-98dc-4cd4bc55fe37","total_cost_usd":0.40632949999999995,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":32219,"cache_read_input_tokens":197489,"output_tokens":2264,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":32219,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":7,"outputTokens":2264,"cacheReadInputTokens":197489,"cacheCreationInputTokens":32219,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.35674825000000004,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":24,"outputTokens":2868,"cacheReadInputTokens":82160,"cacheCreationInputTokens":21601,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.04958125000000001,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"All five amendments identify genuine correctness issues in the milestone record service. The trait default implementations for `record_task_run_start` and `append_event_if_missing` have non-atomic read-check-write sequences that cannot enforce their invariants under concurrency, while the FS adapter correctly overrides with locks. The service-level functions `record_bead_start` and `update_task_run` both perform snapshot read-reconcile-write outside any lock, creating lost-update windows. The ordering bug in `record_bead_start` (writing lineage before validating terminal state) is a concrete partial-mutation defect. I accept all five.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-6-93044933","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified in service.rs:96-155: the default `record_task_run_start` performs read_task_runs, validates exclusivity/finalization invariants, then appends — three separate non-atomic calls. The FS override at fs.rs:2526-2602 correctly acquires an advisory file lock before the entire read-check-write sequence. The default creates a false sense of safety since its invariant checks (active bead exclusivity, finalized-run rejection) are trivially defeated by interleaving. Either removing the default or prominently documenting its non-concurrency-safety is the right fix."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-81c4543f","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed in service.rs:65-79: the default `append_event_if_missing` calls `read_journal()` then checks for duplicates then calls `append_event()` as separate operations. The FS override at fs.rs:2306-2327 correctly holds the journal lock across both the read and append. Two concurrent callers using the default can both observe absence and both append, violating the 'if missing' semantics. Same fix applies: remove the default or document it as non-concurrency-safe."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-459caba1","decision":"accept","rationale":"In service.rs:462-496, `record_bead_start` reads the snapshot (line 463), calls `record_task_run_start` (line 470, which holds the lineage lock internally), re-reads lineage and reconciles (line 480-484), then writes the snapshot (line 487). The snapshot read and write are completely outside the lineage lock. A concurrent `update_task_run` (service.rs:593-614) follows the same unprotected pattern. The interleaving scenario is concrete: thread A reads snapshot, thread B completes a bead and writes snapshot with Ready status, thread A then overwrites with its stale Active snapshot. This is a real lost-update defect even if current usage is mostly single-threaded."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-0ee39bfb","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a concrete ordering bug. In `record_bead_start` (service.rs:462-496), the first reconcile at line 464-468 reads the current snapshot and lineage. Then `record_task_run_start` at line 470 appends a Running row to task-runs.ndjson. The second reconcile at line 480-484 re-reads lineage (now including the new Running row) and sets `active_bead`. But at line 250-258, `reconcile_snapshot_from_lineage` rejects having an active bead on a terminal milestone. So for a completed/abandoned milestone: the Running row is already persisted in lineage, but the reconcile fails, returning an error. The lineage file now has a stray Running entry that will cause subsequent starts to fail. The terminal-state rejection must happen before the lineage mutation."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-ff09cb64","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed by reading both `record_bead_start` (service.rs:462-496) and `update_task_run` (service.rs:571-625). In both functions, the lineage mutation (record_task_run_start / update_task_run on the trait) is locked internally by the FS adapter, but the subsequent snapshot read-reconcile-write cycle (lines 480-487 for start, lines 605-614 for update) runs without any lock. The example is feasible: thread A finalizes bead-1 via update_task_run, computes Ready snapshot; thread B starts bead-2, computes Active snapshot and writes it; thread A then writes its stale Ready snapshot, hiding the active bead-2. The lineage file correctly records bead-2 as Running, but status.json says Ready with no active_bead. This is a real state inconsistency."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"532c0327-8bf4-4083-b7cb-dc70bd85916c"}
